        <div>
          <h3 style="margin-bottom: 1rem;"><span aria-hidden="true">📖</span> My Story</h3>
          <p class="lead" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
            "For 20 years, I've been teaching at NJIT. I've watched students go to work at Fortune 100 companies. I've seen technology transform industries. But I've also studied history—and I know that every major transition creates winners and losers based on who has <strong>ACCESS to education</strong> and whether stakeholders <strong>COORDINATE effectively</strong>."
          </p>

          <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
            I started as an adjunct instructor in 2007, eventually becoming Director of the Web Systems Program. Along the way, I've designed courses that have been used by 500+ students, built curricula that Fortune 100 companies recruited from, and watched Newark-area students land six-figure jobs.
          </p>

          <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
            But it's not enough. For every student who makes it, there are dozens of community members who never even knew the opportunity existed. For every business that hires our graduates, there are dozens struggling to upskill their existing workforce. For every successful training program, there are dozens that fail because they can't coordinate stakeholders.
          </p>

          <p style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
            <strong>AI is different.</strong> It's moving faster than any previous transition. We have maybe 3-5 years to get this right before the gap becomes insurmountable. So I'm dedicating the next chapter of my career to ensuring Newark—and communities like it—don't get left behind.
          </p>

          <div style="background: var(--color-surface); padding: 2rem; border-radius: 8px; margin: 2rem 0;">
            <h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem;"><span aria-hidden="true">🎓</span> Professional Background</h4>
            <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
              <li><strong>20 years at NJIT</strong> (2007-present) — Adjunct to Director of Web Systems Program</li>
              <li><strong>500+ students taught</strong> — Many now at FAANG companies, Fortune 100 employers</li>
              <li><strong>Curriculum recognized by Fortune 100</strong> — Industry-standard quality and practices</li>
              <li><strong>900+ LinkedIn connections</strong> — NJIT alumni, industry leaders, regional network</li>
              <li><strong>CTO, Anthiem Ventures</strong> — Real-world entrepreneurial experience</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <h3 style="margin: 2rem 0 1rem;"><span aria-hidden="true">💭</span> The Philosophy: EverydayAI</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
            I'm not an AI researcher. I'm not a policy expert. I'm a teacher who studies history. And when I look at the printing press, the industrial revolution, the internet—I see the same pattern every time:
          </p>
          <ol style="margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
            <li><strong>Powerful technology emerges</strong> that can dramatically increase productivity</li>
            <li><strong>Early adopters thrive</strong> while others don't even know the opportunity exists</li>
            <li><strong>Stakeholders fail to coordinate</strong>—educators, businesses, communities, government all act separately</li>
            <li><strong>The gap becomes permanent</strong>—whole communities left behind for generations</li>
          </ol>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
            <strong>AI is following the exact same pattern, just faster.</strong> My book "EverydayAI" (coming 2026) argues we can learn from everyday history to make different choices this time. We know what works. We just need to execute.
          </p>

          <h3 style="margin: 2rem 0 1rem;"><span aria-hidden="true">🌉</span> Why the "AI Bridge" Initiative?</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
            The gap isn't technical—it's coordination. We have all the pieces:
          </p>
          <ul style="margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
            <li>🎓 <strong>Education:</strong> NJIT can teach world-class AI skills</li>
            <li>🏢 <strong>Business:</strong> Companies desperately need AI-skilled workers</li>
            <li>🏘️ <strong>Community:</strong> Residents need accessible training and opportunity</li>
            <li>🏛️ <strong>Government:</strong> Grants and workforce development funding exists</li>
          </ul>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
            But they're not connected. The AI Bridge Initiative is literally a bridge—connecting stakeholders who need each other but aren't talking. It's not rocket science. It's just coordination.
          </p>

          <h3 style="margin: 2rem 0 1rem;"><span aria-hidden="true">⚡</span> Why Now? Why This Matters</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
            We have a <strong>$38 trillion national debt</strong>. Our economy has two choices:
          </p>
          <ol style="margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
            <li><strong>Dramatically increase productivity</strong> through AI (which requires training workers)</li>
            <li><strong>Print money</strong> to pay the debt (which causes massive inflation)</li>
          </ol>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
            This isn't charity. This isn't idealism. This is <strong>economic survival</strong>. If we don't get AI right—if we let it create massive inequality and leave communities behind—we're choosing inflation over productivity. We're choosing economic decline.
          </p>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
            <strong>The stakes have never been higher. And the timeline is short.</strong> That's why I'm all-in on this initiative.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
